<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF9EC11BB9FB24FEFB5DF9A1" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9EC11BB9FB24FEFB5DF9A1" blockId="16.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BB9FB24FEFE8FFA34" bold="true" box="[199,322,1410,1436]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="85A4D2F7FF9EC11BBBB324FFFC22FA35" authority="(Diakonoff, 1951)" baseAuthorityName="Diakonoff" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[655,1007,1410,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Panplatyceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serpentina">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BBBB324FFFCD2FA34" box="[655,799,1411,1436]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">T. serpentina</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="2635D485FF9EC11BBA1124FFFC2AFA35" author="Diakonoff, A." box="[813,999,1410,1437]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" pagination="59 - 94" refId="ref21960" refString="Diakonoff, A. (1951 - 1952) Entomological results from the Swedish expedition 1934 to Burma and British India. Lepid. Microlepidoptera I. Arkiv for Zoologi, 3 (6), 59 - 94." type="journal article" year="1951">Diakonoff, 1951</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
in both appearance and male genitalia. It can be distinguished by the valva narrowed from base to basal 2/5, parallel-sided from basal 2/5 to 3/5 and thereafter narrowed to apex, the juxta widened posteriorly and narrowed anteriorly; in 
<taxonomicName id="85A4D2F7FF9EC11BBD4A24B7FAC4FA4C" baseAuthorityName="Diakonoff" baseAuthorityYear="1951" box="[1142,1289,1483,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Panplatyceros" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serpentina">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BBD4A24B7FAC4FA4C" box="[1142,1289,1483,1508]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">T. serpentina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the valva is narrowed from base to apex; and the juxta is rectangular (
<bibRefCitation id="2635D485FF9EC11BBA202493FC03F9A1" author="Gozmany, L." box="[796,974,1519,1545]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" refId="ref22100" refString="Gozmany, L. (1978) Lecithoceridae. In: Amsel, H. G., Reisser, H. &amp; Gregor, F. (Eds.), Microlepidoptera Palaearctica. Vol. 5. Georg Fromme &amp; Co., Wien, pp. 1 - 306." type="book" year="1978">Gozmány 1978</bibRefCitation>
: Pl. 49, fig. 145).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF9EC11AB9FB276EFC17FD95" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9EC11BB9FB276EFCFBF985" blockId="16.[151,1437,1266,2013]" box="[199,822,1554,1581]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BB9FB276EFE94F984" bold="true" box="[199,345,1554,1580]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Description.</emphasis>
Adult (
<figureCitation id="DA9FB5F1FF9EC11BB891276FFDCCF985" box="[429,513,1555,1581]" captionStart="FIGURES 13‒18" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1834,1858]" captionTargetBox="[151,1432,181,1803]" captionTargetId="figure-20@21.[151,1435,181,1810]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 13‒18. Adults of Torodora spp. (dorsal view). 13. T. spectabilis sp. nov., paratype, female, slide No. YS20261; 14. T. stilliformis sp. nov., paratype, male, slide No. YS20117; 15. T. strigulosa sp. nov., holotype, male, slide No. LSR13240; 16. T. ventrimaculata sp. nov., holotype, male, slide No. YS20350; 17. T. xizangensis sp. nov., paratype, female, slide No. YS20387; 18. T. zhejiangensis sp. nov., paratype, female. Scale bars = 2.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521250" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521250/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
). Wingspan 20.0‒21.5 mm.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9EC11BB9FB274BFC89F9DD" blockId="16.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BB9FB274BFEC9F9F9" box="[199,260,1591,1617]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Head</emphasis>
orange yellow entirely; antenna orange yellow in basal 2/3, greyish black in distal 1/3. Labial palpus orange yellow, third palpomere as long as second palpomere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9EC11BB9FB2703FE25F8D9" blockId="16.[151,1437,1266,2013]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BB9FB2703FED5F931" box="[199,280,1663,1689]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Thorax</emphasis>
and tegula orange yellow. Forewing with costal margin slightly arched, apex obtuse, termen shallowly concave; ground color orange yellow; dorsum with a large subrectangular purplish brown blotch from subbase to tornus, its inner margin reaching costal margin, upper margin reaching anterior margin of discal cell and stalk of R 
<subScript id="DE20AB31FF9EC11BB9962781FF18F8A3" attach="left" box="[170,213,1789,1803]" fontSize="6" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">3+4+5</subScript>
, shallowly concave medially, outer margin obtuse; fringe orange yellow except purplish brown along dorsum. Hindwing grey except pale yellow around apex and along termen; fringe pale yellow along termen, grey along dorsum. Legs orange yellow except white on femora, purplish brown at apex of fore and mid tibiae, as well as at middle and apex of hind tibia.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9EC11AB9FB2607FE2CFECD" blockId="16.[151,1437,1266,2013]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,681]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="18" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9EC11BB9FB2607FEBDF83D" box="[199,368,1915,1941]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="DA9FB5F1FF9EC11BB8BF2607FE16F83D" box="[387,475,1915,1941]" captionStart="FIGURES 31‒36" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1855,1879]" captionTargetBox="[154,1427,194,1811]" captionTargetId="figure-23@24.[151,1435,181,1830]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 31‒36. Male genitalia of Torodora spp. 31. T. spectabilis sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20260; 32. T. stilliformis sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20116; 33. T. strigulosa sp. nov., holotype, slide No. LSR13240; 34. T. ventrimaculata sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20350; 35. T. xizangensis sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20386; 36. T. zhejiangensis sp. nov., holotype, slide No. YS20115; 36a. Enlarged posterolateral lobes of the juxta, slide No. YS20342. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521256" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521256/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
). Uncus elongate triangular, apex narrowly rounded. Gnathos with mesial process wide at base, narrowed to basal 3/5, distal 2/5 slender to a pointed apex, curved ventrad before apex. Valva broad basally, slightly narrowed to basal 2/5, parallel-sided from basal 2/5 to 3/5, thereafter narrowed to rounded apex; costa gently arched basally, shallowly concave medially, straight distally; ventral margin gently arched medially, extending obliquely dorsad distally; sacculus wide at base, narrowed to basal 2/5 of ventral margin of valva, straight ventrally. Vinculum narrow, rounded on anterior margin. Juxta widened posteriorly, narrowed anteriorly, shortly and widely produced on posterior margin, obtusely rounded on anterior margin; posterolateral lobe short, setose. Aedeagus shorter than valva, straight, broad basally, tapered to obtuse apex; cornutus situated distally, banded, about 1/3 length of aedeagus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9FC11AB9FB2013FC17FD95" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9FC11AB9FB2013FE4BFE21" box="[199,390,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Female genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="DA9FB5F1FF9FC11AB8A82013FE25FE22" box="[404,488,367,394]" captionStart="FIGURES 46‒49" captionStartId="27.[151,264,1930,1954]" captionTargetBox="[225,1358,196,1890]" captionTargetId="figure-20@27.[213,1374,181,1907]" captionTargetPageId="27" captionText="FIGURES 46‒49. Female genitalia of Torodora spp. 46. T. spectabilis sp. nov., slide No. YS20261; 47. T. stilliformis sp. nov., slide No. YS20328; 48. T. xizangensis sp. nov., slide No. YS20387; 49. T. zhejiangensis sp. nov., slide No. YS20317. All paratypes. Scale bars = 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521262" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521262/files/figure.png" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
). Eighth abdominal sternite notched medially on posterior margin, with a rectangular process at middle on anterior margin. Apophyses posteriores about twice length of apophyses anteriores. Antrum membranous, funnel-shaped. Ductus bursae about twice length of corpus bursae, narrowed posteriorly, twisted once medially, with sparse conic spines from about posterior 1/4 to middle; ductus seminalis as wide as posterior part of ductus bursae, arising from posterior 1/4 of ductus bursae. Corpus bursae small rounded; signum situated at middle, triangular, denticulate, with two larger, triangular teeth on anterior margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF9FC11AB9FB233AFDECFDC9" box="[199,545,582,609]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9FC11AB9FB233AFDECFDC9" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,681]" box="[199,545,582,609]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9FC11AB9FB233AFEACFDC8" bold="true" box="[199,353,582,608]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingCountry id="3AB3E9E4FF9FC11AB85B233BFE67FDC9" box="[359,426,583,609]" name="China" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion id="80606796FF9FC11AB885233BFDD8FDC9" box="[441,533,583,609]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="0ABEFAFFFF9FC11AB9FB2317FEC9FD01" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="421BA974FF9FC11AB9FB2317FEC9FD01" blockId="17.[151,1437,151,681]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9FC11AB9FB2317FE83FD2D" bold="true" box="[199,334,619,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<taxonomicName id="85A4D2F7FF9FC11ABA6F2317FC06FD2D" authorityName="Yu et Wang" authorityYear="2022" box="[851,971,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Torodora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="18" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spectabilis">
<emphasis id="70D07566FF9FC11ABA6F2317FC06FD2D" box="[851,971,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="18">spectabilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, referring to the remarkable blotch on the forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
